\end_layout

\end_inset

 Does delivering the odorant lead to a change (typically an increase) in
 the airspeed at the outlet? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout aEnumerate (ClassicThesis)
\begin_inset Flex CT - Spaced Low Small Caps
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Odorant phase.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

Odorants can be in liquid phase, pure or diluted, or can be contained on
 a solid substrate like a filter paper.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These design decisions come with intrinsic tradeoffs.
 Positioning the valve upstream of the valve means that no odorant is directly
 in contact with the valve, and that in principle, the valve is not contaminated
 by the odorant.
 This has led previous work to use a single valve with many different odorants,
 lowering cost and speeding up the process of delivering several different
 odorants 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "deBruyne:1999uh,Hallem:2006iu"

\end_inset

.
 In this configuration, air flows over and depletes the odorant 
\emph on
only
\emph default
 when the stimulus is being delivered.
 
\begin_inset Marginal
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
However, odorants can diffuse when there is no flow, contaminating valves
 upstream of odorants
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This has the advantage of conserving odorant, as all odorant that enters
 gas phase is delivered to the preparation, a feature that could be useful
 when small quantities of odorant are used, for example, when the odorant
 is expensive or hard to produce, like a pheromone.
 Positioning the valve upstream of the odorant also necessarily introduces
 transients in the signal, as the odorant-vapor system is never at steady
 state.
 On the other hand, positioning the valve downstream of the odorant means
 that the odorant flows through the valve, necessitating using a different
 valve for every odorant to avoid cross-contamination.
 The costs of choosing to place valves downstream of odorants, both of material
 and time, can be signficant if hundreds of odorant-receptor combinations
 are to be tested, as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hallem:2004ht,Hallem:2006iu,Kreher:2005va,Mathew:2013ic"

\end_inset

.
 Since the valve is downstream of the odorant, air always flows over the
 odorant, and the valve diverts this odorised airstream either to waste
 (normally), or to the preparation.
 While this design consumes more odorant, the liquid odorant in its chamber
 can reach steady state with the vapor in the chamber, and the state of
 the valve downstream of the odorant does not disturb this equilibirum,
 which could lead to more reproducible stimuli.
 
\end_layout

