\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Odorants are typically diluted in mineral oil or paraffin oil, since odorants
 evaporating from paraffin oil are believed to exhibit a linear relationship
 between their liquid and gas phase concentrations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Brockerhoff:1999jg"

\end_inset

.
 Traditionally, serial dilutions of odorants have been prepared in paraffin
 oil, and small quantities of these mixtures have been applied to filter
 paper disks in glass Pastuer pipettes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Clyne:1997eh"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Cartridges
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 so prepared contain odorant in the gas phase that evaporates from the filter
 paper disk, and are typically used in conjuction with a valve before the
 cartridge, that pushes the odorized air towards the preparation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "deBruyne:1999uh,Hallem:2006iu"

\end_inset

.
 An alternative is to use a vial containing a larger quantitity of the diluted
 odorant liquid, either with a very small headspace, as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nagel:2011jj"

\end_inset

, to ensure that the headspace gas phase concentration is dominated by the
 bulk of the liquid odorant, or with a larger headspace, as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kim:2010ds"

\end_inset

, to create a large volume of odorized air that can be pushed towards the
 preparation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Diluting odorants in liquid phase using mineral or paraffin oil leads to
 intrinsic non-reproducability, since every passage of air over the mixture
 depletes the liquid phase concentration of the odorant and the diluent
 to different extents.
 In the extreme case, mineral oil and paraffin are practically involatile
 and every passage of air over depletes the odorant but not the diluent.
 Since the gas phase concentration of odorant in the headspace depends on
 the liquid phase concentration of odorant in a region close to the boundary
 layer, the gas phase concentration of the odorant continuiously decreases
 with time.
 One way to ameliorate this depletion is to use a very large volume of odorant
 mixture, and to stir the mixture continuiously
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Martelli:2013it"

\end_inset

.
 Stirring expands the effective boundary layer of the mixture, and enables
 the gas phase concentration of the headspace to track the liquid phase
 concentration more closely.
 However, stirring odorants may be impractical in some applications, especially
 in the cramped and electrically sensitive encironment of an electrophysiology
 rig, and doesn't ultimately solve the problem of odorant depletion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Delivering odorants: stimulus waveforms 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Odorant stimuli can be defined by their chemical identity, amplitude and
 temporal structure.
 Choice of odorant, and their concentration define the first two features.
 Pulses of odorant have been used as a common stimulus waveform 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Clyne:1997eh,Larsson:2004bx"

\end_inset

, as they are easily generated by briefly turning on a valve that directs
 odorised air to the preparation.
 These simple stimuli reveal whether the neuron of interest responds to
 the odorant tested or not, and can also reveal the kinetics of response
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "deBruyne:1999uh,Hallem:2004ht"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More complicated stimuli are difficult to generate due to two reasons: (i)
 the evaporation of volatile odorants makes delivering long stimuli challenging
 and (ii) a valve has only two positions, on or off, limiting the temporal
 structure of the odorant stimulus.
 Various studies have worked around these limitations to deliver more complex
 odorant stimuli.
 Using large volumes of liquid odorant to fight depletion, some studies
 have used a valve to randomly turn on and off an odorant airstream, generating
 a random binary signal that has been used to characterise the response
 propeorties of ORNs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "French:2007js,Schuckel:2008gz,Martelli:2013it,Nagel:2011jj"

\end_inset

.
 While stimuli generated this way are typically bimodal, corresponding to
 on and off states of the valves, unimodal stimulus distributions can be
 achieved with combinations of valve switching time and some odorants with
 slower intrinsic kinetics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Martelli:2013it"

\end_inset

.
 Other studies have used custom-made olfactometers using computer controlled
 MFCs to generate triangular, staircase and Gaussian stimulus waveforms
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kim:2015dm,Kim:2010ds"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Measuring odorants
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Light can be measured by cameras and sound by microphones, and the sensitivity
 and range of these electronic sensors can exceed that of the human eye
 or ear.
 However, no equivalent electronic 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nose
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 has been developed.
 Therefore, measuring odorants is not standard practice in olfactory research.
 One of the earliest atempts to measure odorant stimuli used gas-chromatography
 on the headspace 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hoskovec:1993dp"

\end_inset

.
 Though cumbersome, slow and expensive, gas-chromatographic techniques are
 still useful, espeically in studies of the chemical ecology of olfactory
 animals, and coupled with presentations of many odorants eluted from a
 single, natural odor source 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Dweck:2016gy"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another approach is to use a visible tracer and measure the stimulus optically.
 While this is an indirect measure, and is not informative of the absolute
 amount of odorant, it can reveal the spatial and temporal pattern of odorant
 stimuli, and has been used in applications where the precise timing of
 odorant stimuli is key 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Szyszka:2014in"

\end_inset

.
 Another optical method is to use 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acf{FT-IR}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This method has been used to measure the gas-phase concentration of known
 odorants from their absorption using the Beer-Lambert law 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Louis:2008du,Schulze:2015bt"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

