\begin_layout Subsection
How to deliver pulses of odorant with different intensities 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest olfactory stimuli that can be delivered is a short pulse of
 a single odorant.
 Using short pulses of odorant lets experimenters determine if neurons and
 receptors of interest respond to this particular odorant 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hallem:2004ht,Hallem:2006iu"

\end_inset

, and reveal their dynamical response properties 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hallem:2004ht,Su:2011hd,Martelli:2013it"

\end_inset

.
 Using short pulses of odorant with different amplitudes estimates the dose-resp
onse curve of that neuron, permitting the quantification of its sensitivity
 to that odorant 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "deBruyne:2001ur"

\end_inset

.
 Typically, pulses of odorant have been delivered by forcing air through
 catridges containing a filter paper with a small quantitity of odorant
 diluted in Paraffin Oil.
 Stimulus duration is controlled by the length of time air is forced through
 the catridge, and stimulus intensity is controlled by the liquid phase
 dilution of the odorant in Paraffin Oil.
 This means that different catrdiges have to be prepared for different desired
 stimulus intensities, making the process potentially cumbersome.
 Furthermore, since odorants contaminate the entire inner surface of the
 cartrdige, cartridges typically are discarded after a certain number of
 uses
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Larter:2016gv"

\end_inset

, making this method wasteful.
 Since considerable time may elapse between cartridge preparation and applicatio
n, a previous study has found that refrigerating cartridges is required
 to ensure reliability 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Andersson:2012bs"

\end_inset

, further complicating this process.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pulses of odorant delivered this way can show dramatic variation from trial
 to trial, especially for volatile odorants with large vapour pressures
 (Fig.
 
