\begin_layout Standard
Here, we propose using pure odorants contained in a scintillation vial to
 deliver pulses of odorant.
 Pulse height is controlled by varying the flow through the scintilltion
 vial using a 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acf{MFC}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This approach has several advantages over the earlier method.
 First, since pure odorant is used, evaporation of the odorant does nto
 change the effective concentration fo the odorant that remains in the scintilla
tion vial, and the gas phase concnetration of the headspace in the vial
 remains constant, as long as there is some odorant left in the vial.
 Second, it greatly simplifies the apparatus needed to deliver odorants:
 Pasteur pipettes, filter papers, etc.
 are not needed, and there is no need to precisely measure the amount of
 odorant in the scintilaltion vial.
 Third, pulses of several intensities can be delivered with the same apparatus,
 enabling automation of typical experiments.
 Finally, this approach creates no waste, as all parts of the system can
 be re-used, including the scintillation vial.
 When odorant is depleted, the scintillation vial can be refilled with more
 pure odorant.
 Pulses delivered using this method are more reliable from trial to trial
 than the earlier method, and do not show any signficant decay in amplitude
 over 20 trials (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:methods-pulse-variability"

\end_inset

, bottom row).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The primary reason to deliver odorant pulses of different intensities to
 a neuron is to determine its dose response curve.
 These results suggest that there are two approaches to this problem.
 First, one can embrace the intrinisc decay in pulse amplitude associated
 with the older method, and measure the stimulus 
\emph on
and
\emph default
 response, and use the measured stimulus to determine the dose-response
 curve.
 Second, one can use MFCs and pure odorants to generate reprodible pulses,
 and utilize the unitary nature of this hardware approach to automate the
 experiment.
 
\end_layout

